ROGUE(6)                         Games Manual                         ROGUE(6)



[1mNAME[0m
       rogue - Exploring The Dungeons of Doom

[1mSYNOPSIS[0m
       [1m@PROGRAM@ [22m[ [1m-r [22m] [ [4msave_file[24m ] [ [1m-s [22m] [ [1m-d [22m] [ [1m-V [22m]

[1mDESCRIPTION[0m
       [4mRogue[24m  is a computer fantasy game with a new twist.  It is crt oriented
       and the object of the game is to survive the attacks  of  various  mon-
       sters and get a lot of gold, rather than the puzzle solving orientation
       of most computer fantasy games.

       To get started you really only need to know two commands.  The  command
       [1m?   [22mwill  give  you  a list of the available commands and the command [1m/[0m
       will identify the things you see on the screen.

       To win the game (as opposed to merely playing to  beat  other  people's
       high  scores)  you  must locate the Amulet of Yendor which is somewhere
       below the 20th level of  the  dungeon  and  get  it  out.   Nobody  has
       achieved  this  yet and if somebody does, they will probably go down in
       history as a hero among heroes.

       When the game ends, either by your death, when you quit, or if you  (by
       some  miracle) manage to win, [4mrogue[24m will give you a list of the top-ten
       scorers.  The scoring is based entirely upon how  much  gold  you  get.
       There is a 10% penalty for getting yourself killed.

       If  [4msave_file[24m  is  specified, rogue will be restored from the specified
       saved game file.  If the [1m-r [22moption is used, the save game file is  pre-
       sumed to be the default.

       The [1m-s [22moption will print out the list of scores.

       The [1m-d [22moption will kill you and try to add you to the score file.

       The [1m-V [22mwill print the release and version (same as the rogue v command)
       and then exit.

       For more detailed directions, read the document [4mA[24m [4mGuide[24m [4mto[24m [4mthe[24m [4mDungeons[0m
       [4mof[24m [4mDoom.[0m

[1mOPTIONS[0m
       The [1mrogue [22mgame options may be displayed and changed by using the [1mo [22mcom-
       mand.

       The option names are:

       [1mterse / noterse[0m

              Useful for those who are tired of the sometimes lengthy messages
              of rogue.

              This  is  a  useful option to enable when playing on an histori-
              cally slow terminal.

              Default: [1mnoterse[0m

              Recommendation: [1mnoterse[0m

       [1mflush / noflush[0m

              If this option is set, typeahead is thrown away after each round
              of battle.

              This  is  useful for those who type far ahead, and then watch in
              dismay as a Bat kills them.

              Default: [1mnoflush[0m

              Recommendation: [1mflush[0m

       [1mjump / nojump[0m

              If this option is set, running moves will not be displayed until
              you reach the end of the move.

              This  is  a  useful option to enable when playing on an histori-
              cally slow terminal.

              Default: [1mnojump[0m

              Recommendation: [1mjump[0m

       [1mseefloor / noseefloor[0m

              Display the floor around you on the screen as you  move  through
              dark rooms.

              This  is  a useful option to disable when playing on an histori-
              cally slow terminal.

              Default: [1mseefloor[0m

              Recommendation: [1mseefloor[0m

       [1mpassgo / nopassgo[0m

              Follow turnings in passageways.  If you run in a passage and you
              run  into  stone or a wall, rogue will see if it can turn to the
              right or left.  If it can only turn one way, it will  turn  that
              way. If it can turn either or neither, it will stop.

              This  algorithm  can sometimes lead to slightly confusing occur-
              rences to some people, which is why it defaults to false.

              Default: [1mnopassgo[0m

              Recommendation: [1mpassgo[0m

       [1mtombstone / notombstone[0m

              Print out the tombstone at the end if you get killed.

              This is a useful option to disable when playing on  an  histori-
              cally slow terminal.

              Default: [1mtombstone[0m

              Recommendation: [1mtombstone[0m

       [1minven[22m=style

              Set the inventory style to one of: [1moverwrite[22m, [1mslow[22m, or [1mclear[22m.

              With  [1moverwrite[22m,  the  top lines of the map are overwritten with
              the list when inventory is requested, or when "Which item do you
              wish  to ...?" questions are answered with a [1m* [22m(asterisk).  How-
              ever, if the list is longer than  a  screenful,  the  screen  is
              cleared.

              With  [1mslow[22m, lists are displayed one item at a time on the top of
              the screen.

              With [1mclear[22m, the screen is cleared, the list  is  displayed,  and
              then the dungeon level is re-displayed.

              Default: [1mclear[0m

              Recommendation: [1moverwrite[0m

       [1mname[22m=rogue-name

              This  is  the  name of your character, as displayed in the rogue
              score file.

              Default: [1m<<your account name>>[0m

              Recommendation: [1m<<leave as default>>[0m

       [1mfruit[22m=fruit-name

              This should hold the name of a fruit that you enjoy eating.   It
              is basically a whimsy that rogue uses in a couple of places.

              Default: [1mslime-mold[0m

              Recommendation: [1mapple[0m

       [1mfile[22m=rogue-save-path

              The default file name for saving the game.

              Default: [1m~/.rogue.save[0m

              Recommendation: [1m<<leave as default>>[0m

       [1mscore[22m=rogue-score-path

              The path of the rogue score file.

              Default: [1m~/.rogue.scr[0m

              Recommendation: [1m<<leave as default>>[0m

       [1mlock[22m=rogue-lock-path

              The rogue lock file used to protect the rogue score file.

              Default: [1m~/.rogue.lck[0m

              Recommendation: [1m<<leave as default>>[0m

[1mENVIRONMENT[0m
       The following environment variables affect the execution of [1m$ROGUEOPTS[22m:
       The [1m$ROGUEOPTS [22menvironment variable may be used to change the [1mrogue  [22mat
       startup, rather than having to use the [1mo [22mcommand each time you play.

       The  [1m$ROGUEOPTS [22menvironment variable would be a string that is a series
       of comma separated values, with booleans being stated as "name"  (true)
       or "noname" (false), and strings being "name=....", with the string be-
       ing defined up to a comma or the end of the entire option string.

       As an example, here is a recommended [1m$ROGUEOPTS  [22menvironment  value  to
       set in your environment:

            export ROGUEOPTS="noterse,flush,jump,seefloor,passgo,tombstone,in-
            ven=overwrite,fruit=apple"

       If the [1m$ROGUEOPTS [22menvironment value is missing or  empty,  the  default
       options will be used.  Unknown options are silently ignored.

[1mFILES[0m
       [1mLock File:[0m

            @LOCKFILE@

       The  rogue lock file is a zero-length file that must be writable by the
       user.  It is used to help prevent multiple processes on the  local  ma-
       chine from writing to the rogue score file at the same time.

       If  the  rogue  lock file does not exist, the lock file will be created
       when updating the rogue score file.

       [1mSave file:[0m

            @SAVEFILE@

       The rogue save file is created whenever you use the [1mS [22mcommand  to  save
       the  game,  or if certain signals are successfully caught and the "auto
       save" action is successfully completed.

       A rogue save file is not guaranteed to restore in a different system.

       If the rogue save file does not exist, it will be created when  a  game
       is saved.

       [1mScore File:[0m

            @SCOREFILE@

       The  rogue  score  file  contains the top rogue games, in terms of gold
       collected.  By default, 10 rogue score are saved.

       The rogue score file must be writable by the user.

       The length of the rogue score file is usually 112 bytes per score slot,
       so the default rogue score file size is 1120 bytes.

       Unlike  the  BSD  rogue  game  on the Vax/pdp, rogue keeps track of top
       rogue scores, no matter how they were played, and no matter if they won
       the game or not.

       If the rogue score file does not exist, [1mrogue [22mwill create it.

       If the rogue score file is corrupted, or the format is too old, then an
       error message will be displayed advising that the rogue score  file  be
       removed.

